initial_story:
The National Police Air Service has shared a video of what it was like flying through Storm Gerrit's heavy winds, in a helicopter.

The footage, which was captured from inside the cockpit, shows the chopper rocking side to side, after being hit by winds of up to 80mph (128km/h).

Posting on X, formerly known as Twitter, the NPAS said "If you think it's windy down there, spare a thought for us up here in our flying washing machine".

The footage was filmed near Lea Valley reservoirs, North London.
stories: The shaky camera captures the pilot's focused face as he navigates the turbulent air, the roar of the engines drowning out any sound of his thoughts as he works to keep the aircraft stable. The GPS display on the dashboard flickers wildly, showing the chopper's erratic path through the storm clouds.

Heavy rain lashes against the cockpit windows, reducing visibility to near zero as the pilot struggles to maintain altitude, his eyes darting between the instruments and the horizon as he tries to find a gap in the thick cloud cover. The altimeter reads 500 feet, and dropping, the pilot's grip on the controls tightening as he fights to prevent the chopper from crashing onto the treetops below.

The rotor blades thrum in protest as the chopper pitches and rolls, buffeted by the fierce gusts, the sound of the rain drumming against the skin of the aircraft like a thousand tiny drummers. The pilot's voice is low and calm, but his knuckles are white with tension as he growls, "Hang on, it's going to get ugly," just as the warning light on the console begins to flash, signaling a loss of hydraulics.

The hydraulic pump fails with a sickening hiss, leaving the controls sluggish and unresponsive, and the chopper begins to sway alarmingly, its tail dropping towards the ground like a bird with broken wings.

Panic sets in as I grip the cyclic with a mixture of fear and desperation, my eyes scanning the instruments wildly as I struggle to keep the machine level, the wind and the G-forces playing havoc with my senses.

The horizon seems to be tilting violently, the earth below me a blurry haze, and I'm forced to focus on the altimeter and compass to maintain any semblance of control, the words of my training instructor echoing in my mind: "Don't look outside, just fly the plane".

My heart is racing, the muscles in my arms and legs screaming with tension as I fight to keep the plane level, the instruments blurring together in a mad dance before my eyes, and yet, in the periphery of my vision, I can see the storm clouds gathering, thick and menacing, like a living thing, reaching out to consume me whole.

The roar of the engines is almost deafening, the metal creaking and groaning beneath me as I struggle to counter the turbulence, sweat dripping from my brow, my eyes darting wildly between the spinning needles and the rapidly dropping altimeter, while the storm's dark tendrils seem to be wrapping themselves around the plane, sucking the air out of my lungs, and then, just as I think I've got it under control, a lightning bolt slashes across the sky, its jagged edge illuminated by a blinding flash, and I'm catapulted into the heart of the maelstrom, adrift in a sea of chaos and confusion, with no escape in sight.

The instruments are useless, the needle bouncing wildly as the winds buffet the plane, the windshield a blur of rain and mist, and I'm praying to a God I don't believe in to get us through this, the plane shuddering and lurching in every direction, my stomach dropping with each violent jolt, the darkness outside seeping in through the shattered windshield, and I'm screaming into the mic, my voice lost in the cacophony, trying to reach anyone who might be listening, as the storm seems to be growing in intensity, its fury unrelenting, and I'm searching frantically for some way out of this living nightmare.

The altimeter needles spinning wildly, the lights of the panel flickering like fireflies in the dark, and I'm gripping the controls with a desperate sense of futility, my knuckles white with fear, as the storm rages on, its fury unrelenting, the plane careening wildly through the turbulent air, and I'm shouting into the radio, my voice hoarse from fear and exhaustion, hoping against hope that someone, anyone, will hear me, will come to my aid, as the darkness closes in around me, the howling wind, the creaking metal, the screams of the passengers, all blending together in a cacophony of chaos, and I'm wondering if we'll ever see the light of day again.

The words I'm screaming into the radio are drowned out by the din of the storm, my voice lost in the void, as I frantically flip switches and yank levers, trying to find some way to stabilize the aircraft, to counteract the vicious turbulence that's threatening to tear us apart, and in my peripheral vision, I see the faces of my passengers - the terrified screaming, the panicked pleading, the helpless despair - their eyes pleading with me to save them, to get us out of this living nightmare, as the engines groan and cough and struggle to generate even a hint of power, and I'm praying, praying with every fiber of my being that someone, somehow, will get the message, will come to our rescue before it's too late, before the storm finally consumes us all.

The windshield wipers beat back and forth in a frantic rhythm, slicing through the sheets of rain that obscured my view, while the instrument panel flickered and dimmed, as if even the very fabric of reality was straining to be heard over the cacophony of the storm. I felt like I was drowning, suffocating under the weight of responsibility, as I struggled to keep my cool and think clearly. The aircraft was a bucking bronco, shaking and shuddering in every direction, threatening to disintegrate into a thousand pieces at any moment. And yet, amidst the chaos, I saw the pilot's voice, calm and steady, crackle through the comms system, his words a lifeline in the darkness: "Mayday, Mayday... this is aircraft 47-Charlie- Uniform... we are experiencing severe turbulence... request immediate assistance... over." I forced myself to focus, to think, to pray that someone out there would hear our plea for help.

As I keyed the comms switch to respond, the words got stuck in my throat, refusing to budge. My mind was a jumble of panic and uncertainty, my thoughts racing like the storm outside. The silence that followed was oppressive, punctuated only by the wail of the wind and the creaking of the aircraft's metal body. I could feel the weight of the pilot's words, a desperate cry for help in the midst of a maelstrom, echoing through the emptiness of the airwaves.

I took a deep breath, trying to calm the turmoil within, and forced the words out: "This is [callsign], receive you loud and clear. Can you give me your location and situation report?" The wind howled in my ear, and I strained to hear the pilot's response, my heart pounding in my chest like a drum.

"...Romeo-12, this is Eagle-7. I'm north of the crash site, about 10 klicks out. I've got multiple injuries on board, including one critical. We're trying to stabilize them, but it's a mess down here. Over."
"Romeo-12, this is Eagle-7. Roger that, Eagle-7. I've got visuals on your position. It looks like a hostile LZ. Can you give me an update on the situation on the ground? Are you under fire? Over."

"Roger that, Eagle-7. Situation is dire. We're pinned down by small arms fire and taking casualties. Our original LZ has been compromised and we've had to fall back to a secondary position. I've got 3 KIA and several wounded. Need immediate extraction to avoid being overrun. Can you provide cover fire and prepare for a medevac? Over."

"Eagle-7 this is Bluehawk. Roger that, receiving your mayday. Cover fire is en route. I'll have a chopper over your position in 5 mikes. Prepare for extraction. Can you give me a sitrep on the number and location of wounded? I need to adjust our extraction plan. Over."

"Eagle-7 this is Bluehawk. We've got four KIA and six WIA, with multiple gunshot wounds. Wounded are scattered approximately 50 meters north and east of my position. Be advised, the enemy is closing in fast, over."

"Eagle-7, this is Bluehawk. Roger that. Situation is critical. Advise that I have 5 friendly elements in a 360-degree perimeter, attempting to provide cover and return fire. Requesting immediate close air support to pin down the enemy's advance. Vector to my current location ASAP, over."

"Eagle-7, Bluehawk. Situation is grim but understood. Vectoring to your location immediately. Expect to be overhead in 2 minutes. Requesting clearance for dive bomb on the enemy's main force. Are you clear to receive CAS fire, and do you have a designated target to engage? Over."

"CAS-7, Eagle-7. Roger that, situation is dire. We are pinned down by heavy fire and can't hold out much longer. Clear to receive CAS fire. Designated target is the enemy's 57mm antiaircraft gun, located at bearing 270, distance 500 meters. Target's coordinates are 43.7239° N, 39.8258° E. Be advised, we have friendly armor units moving to flank enemy position, hope to have them in position for supporting fire within 5 minutes. Request multiple passes to take out the gun, priority target. Over."
"CAS-7, Eagle-7. Roger that. CAS-7, this is Eagle-7. We have visual on the target. Affirm target, 57mm antiaircraft gun at 43.7239° N, 39.8258° E. Can you confirm your position? Over."
"Eagle-7, this is CAS-7. Roger that. Affirm position is 43.7212° N, 39.8285° E. I'm set up on the target, preparing to engage. Request you give me bearing and range on the enemy emplacement. Over."
"Eagle-7, this is CAS-7. Roger that. Bearing on target is 270 degrees relative to your position, range is approximately 1.2 kilometers. Enemy emplacement is heavily armed, over."
"Eagle-7, CAS-7. Confirm bearing and range. Can you provide more information on enemy emplacement's armament and possible friendly forces in the area, over?"

"Roger that, Eagle-7. Bearing 283 degrees, range approximately 8 kilometers. Enemy emplacement appears to be a well-entrenched position with multiple machine gun nests and possibly a 120mm mortar. Friendly forces in the area include our infantry squad advancing north on axis Bravo-1, supported by Alpha-Company, 1st Battalion. They are approximately 2 kilometers to our east and closing on the enemy position. Request permission to provide air support in the form of a single jet strike, targeting the enemy emplacement, over."

"Eagle-7, this is Control. Permission granted. However, I strongly advise against a single jet strike. The infantry squad needs to soften up that position with a prep strike before you can make a meaningful impact. Request you standby while I arrange for an orbital correction. Meanwhile, keep eyes on the target and report any changes in enemy disposition or friendly forces' progress. Over."

"Eagle-7, roger that. Standing by for orbital correction. I've got visual confirmation of enemy disposition: three enemy emplacements, moderate anti-aircraft fire, and possible armor units assembling at the north end of the facility. Friendly forces have reached the outskirts of the perimeter, awaiting infantry support. No changes to friendly forces' progress. Over."

"Eagle-7, copy that. Recommend we adjust our orbit to provide laser designation for friendly fire support. Suggest we target enemy emplacements first, then shift focus to armor units. Requesting further confirmation of friendly forces' location and ETA for infantry support. Over."

"Eagle-7, this is Phoenix-3. Confirming recommendation to adjust orbit. Targeting priority assigned: enemy emplacements, then armor units. Receiving intermittent coordinates from friendly forces, estimating ETA for infantry support is 10-15 minutes. Requesting further confirmation on friendly forces' location and additional details on emplacements and armor units' status. Advise if any changes to original mission parameters. Over."

"Eagle-7, this is Phoenix-3. Confirming recommendation to adjust orbit is roger that. En route to enemy emplacements, currently 12 km out. Receiving fragmentary reports of friendly forces regrouping near grid sector Sierra-1, awaiting further transmission of coordinates. Enemy armor units spotted moving northward along grid sector Tango-3, estimated speed 40 km/h. Requesting further tactical Intel on emplacement layout and possible ambush points. Advise if any changes to friendly forces' location or estimated time of arrival. Also, is it feasible to provide close air support if necessary? Over."

"Eagle-7, this is Phoenix-3. Affirmative on adjusting orbit, will adjust trajectory to converge on enemy emplacements at 9 km out. Acknowledge fragmentary reports of friendly forces regrouping near Sierra-1, will try to gather more intel on their position and estimated time of arrival. On enemy armor units, confirm speed of 40 km/h and moving north along Tango-3. Requesting immediate update on emplacement layout, including number of troops, vehicle types, and possible ambush points. Advise on feasibility of close air support, specifically PGMs and precision-guided munitions. Also, would you like me to provide real-time updates on friendly forces' location? Over."

"Eagle-7, Phoenix-3. Acknowledge all information. Enemy emplacements confirmed, consisting of 3 howitzers, 2 AA batteries, and approximately 200 troops. Troop density is moderate, with pockets of intense concentration near center of emplacement. Feasibility of close air support remains high, PGMs and precision-guided munitions cleared for use. Request you adjust trajectory to 8 km out for maximum coverage. Would appreciate real-time updates on friendly forces' location, prioritizing Sierra-1 position. Over."

"Eagle-7, this is Command. Acknowledged, all information received. Requesting Sierra-1 position update, as well as any changes in troop density or emplacement movement. Can confirm 2 additional troops spotted on north flank, vicinity 43.7897N 118.2357W. Begin adjusting trajectory to 8 km out, awaiting real-time updates from Sierra-1. Can you also confirm availability of close air support for Sierra-1, and whether PGMs can be employed to support friendly forces in that area? Over."

"Eagle-7, this is Sierra-1. Roger that, command. Reporting position update: 43.7823N 118.2382W. No changes in troop density or emplacement movement to report at this time. Confirmed 2 additional troops spotted on north flank, as previously reported. Close air support available, and PGMs can be employed to support friendly forces in the area. Recommend adjustment of trajectory to 4 km out to accommodate PGM strike package. Requesting permission to engage with PGMs and initiate close air support strike. Over."

"Eagle-7, this is Sierra-1. Roger that, command. Permission granted to engage with PGMs and initiate close air support strike. Coordinate with command for authorization on package composition and clearance for release. Request confirmation on friendly force positions and any critical infrastructure in close proximity to the target. Over."

"Eagle-7, Sierra-1. Roger that, command. Confirm permission granted. We're coordinating with command for package composition and clearance for release. Request additional info on friendly force positions and critical infrastructure within 1-kilometer radius of target. Any updates on hostile forces in area? Over."

"Sierra-1, Eagle-7. Roger that. Friendly force positions are: Alpha-Bravo-1 has secured eastern flank, Charlie-Lima-2 has established perimeter northwest. Critical infrastructure within 1-kilometer radius includes abandoned factory and gas station. Hostile forces reported in sector: 2x armor columns and 3x infantry squads 2 kilometers northeast, moving eastbound at speed 15. Can you provide update on package composition and clearance for release? Waiting on additional intel before giving approval. Over."

"Sierra-1, Eagle-7. Affirm clear on friendly force positions. Package composition is 2 crates containing 4x RPGs, 8x fragmentation grenades, and 1x sniper rifle. Clearance for release pending intel confirmation on hostile forces' actual intent and potential for civilian casualties in the vicinity of the infrastructure. Requesting additional detail on the abandoned factory and gas station's security status and potential hazards. Recommendation to hold off on release until friendly forces can secure the area. Over."

"Roger that, Eagle-7. Sierra-1 affirming clarity on package composition. Requesting confirmation on intel regarding hostile forces' actual intent and potential for civilian casualties in the vicinity of the infrastructure. Please provide additional detail on abandoned factory and gas station's security status and potential hazards. Suggest holding off on release until friendly forces can secure the area. Requesting a sitrep on any observed hostile movements in the area. Also, please confirm if friendly forces have eyes on the package's intended delivery point. Over."

"Eagle-7 this is Sierra-1. Intel suggests hostile forces may be attempting to intercept the package, but exact intent and potential casualties unknown. Abandoned factory is showing signs of recent occupation, with scattered weapons and ammunition on site. Gas station appears compromised, with multiple broken windows and signs of forced entry. Potential hazards include improvised explosive devices, booby traps, and small arms fire. Friendly forces are currently moving to secure the area, ETA approximately 10 minutes. No hostile movement observed in vicinity at this time. Package's intended delivery point is visually confirmed to be secure, with friendly forces in place. Holding off on release until secure escort can be provided. Recommendation is to delay until area is fully secured, over."

"Eagle-7, this is Sierra-1. Roger that, holding position and monitoring situation. Request additional intel on package contents and estimated value. Confirm if any friendly forces were compromised during attempt to secure gas station. Over."

"Eagle-7, Sierra-1. Received and understood. Confirming friendly forces, 3rd Platoon of Charlie-Company, reported no casualties or compromise during attempted secure. As for package contents, preliminary intel suggests high-value data drives, estimated value at $500K. Repeat, no confirmation of exact contents, awaiting further intel from base camp. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1. Eagle-7 copies all. Confirming receipt of package contents intel. Suggest increasing escort detail until further notice. Can you confirm exact location of 3rd Platoon at time of secure? Over."

"Roger that, Eagle-7. Sierra-1 affirms receipt of intel. Confirming escort detail will be increased to maximum until further notice. Third Platoon's last known location was 42-Alpha-Actual, awaiting further updates from 3-2 and 3-4. ETA for re-supply and reinforcement is 02:00 Zulu. Will transmit updated coordinates as soon as received. Over."

"Eagle-7, Sierra-1 acknowledges. Increase in escort detail confirmed. Roger that on Third Platoon's last known location. Re-supply and reinforcement ETA of 02:00 Zulu confirmed. Requesting urgent situation report from 3-2 and 3-4 regarding current status and situation on the ground. Over."

"Echo-4, this is Eagle-7. We copy and confirm Third Platoon's last known location. Requesting same report from 3-2 and 3-4 as per Eagle-7. Additionally, inform 3-2 and 3-4 that we are preparing a backup team to rendezvous at their location. ETA to their location is 02:15 Zulu. Over."

"Roger that, Eagle-7. This is Echo-4. Will relay your message to 3-2 and 3-4. 3-4 reports they were last at Grid Coordinates 877-345, but their current status is unknown. 3-2 has moved to Grid Coordinates 912-123, and will provide an update in 10 minutes. Will confirm backup team's ETA to 3-2's location. Over."

"Roger that, Echo-4. Confirm 3-2's current location. Requesting more detail on backup team's ETA. Will provide ETA to base command. Update 3-2 on expected arrival time of additional personnel. Eagle-7 out."
